Part 1: Functions

1A: Exponential Functions

I developed the exponential function below, which will give an output of NULL if k is not an integer, if k is less than 1, or if k is really large (greater than 100).

Exp <- function(x, k) {
  if (k <1 || k >100 || k %% 1 != 0) {
    cat("value of k must be an integere >=1 and <=100")
    return(NULL)
    }
    answer <- 1
    for(i in 1:k){
      answer <- answer + (x^i)/factorial(i)
    }
    return(answer)
  }

1B: Sample mean and Std deviation functions

I developed the following functions and am showing some of their sample output below.

sample_mean <- function (x) {
  answer <-sum(x)/length(x)
  return(answer)
}

x<-1:100
sample_mean(x)
## [1] 50.5
sample_sd <- function (x) {
  xbar <- sum(x)/length(x)
  diff <- sum((x - xbar)^2)
  inside <- diff/(length(x)-1)
  stdev <- sqrt(inside)
  return(stdev)
  }

sample_sd(x)
## [1] 29.01149

Part 1C: Confidence intervals

I developed a calculate_CI function that has the default of 95% percent, but takes as its inputs x (a vector of length N), and conf (the level of confidence that is desired if not 95%). It calculated the 95% CI of x, and returns a two-item named vector, with the first value named lower_bound and the second value named upper_bound.

I am including two different sample confidence intervals, using two different confidence levels (the default 95% and a more stringent 99%).

calculate_CI <- function (x, conf = 0.95) {
  alpha <- 1 - conf
  degrees_freedom <- length(x) - 1
  t_score <- qt(p = alpha / 2, df = degrees_freedom, lower.tail = FALSE)
  se <- sd(x)/sqrt(length(x))
  lower_bound <- mean(x)-t_score*se
  upper_bound <- mean(x)+t_score*se
  CI <- c(lower_bound = lower_bound, upper_bound=upper_bound)
  return(CI)
}

calculate_CI(x)
## lower_bound upper_bound 
##    44.74349    56.25651
calculate_CI(x, 0.99)
## lower_bound upper_bound 
##    42.88041    58.11959

Part 2: Data Wrangling

I used the Tidy Tuesday datasets for rainfall and temperature and completed the following tasks:

  1. I dropped any rows in the rainfall dataset with NAs (using (complete.cases(.)).
  2. Created a new date column formatted YYYY-MM-DD that is recognizable as a date by R (using lubridates make_date).
  3. Converted the city names to all upper case letters (using tidyverses toupper)
  4. Conducted an inner join between the rainfall and temperature datasets, matching on city name and date, to produce a dataset with 83,964 rows and 13 columns.
rainfall <- readRDS(here("data", "tuesdata_rainfall.RDS"))
temperature <- readRDS(here("data", "tuesdata_temperature.RDS"))

Part 3: Data Visualization

Part 3A: Plotting temperature data over time

I graphed the max and min temperatures from 2014 for each city in the data set, with each trendline shown in a different color. The graph is faceted by city_name to show all cities in one figure.

#Filter for years after 2014 
df <- joined_data %>% filter(year >= 2014)

# Produce summary temp statistics
df <- df %>%
  group_by(date, city_name) %>%
  summarize(
    max_temperature = max(temperature),
    min_temperature = min(temperature),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

#plot
ggplot(df, aes(x=date)) +
 geom_line(aes(y =max_temperature, color = "Max Temperature")) +
  geom_line(aes(y =min_temperature, color = "Min Temperature")) +
  facet_wrap(~city_name)+
  labs(title = "Max and Min Temperatures Since 2014 in Major Australian Cities",
       subtitle = "Little Change in Overall Max/Min Temperature Variability in the Last Decade",
       caption = "This graph was produced by Mary de Boer",
      x = "Date since 2014",
      y = "Temperature in Celsisus") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Max Temperature" = "red", "Min Temperature" = "blue"))

###Part 3B: Plotting rainfall over time

  1. I chose to design my function to take as its arguments any version of the city name supplied (upper, lower, in quotes, without) and year as its two arguments. I rendered the city_name as an all-caps character and also kept a title case version to use for the final graphics. Then, I included code to check whether the year and city name exist in the data set. I used the double ampersand to make sure that the first item was evaluated first. the in operator (%in%) which checks if elements in one vector exist within another one, and the exclamation point to negate the expression. If the city_name and/or the year is not in the data frame, it will give an error message. For the actual plot, I used the code mostly as supplied, incorporating colors but also I learned that I had to add the ! before the name of the input in order for R to read it as an input rather than as the corresponding column title from the joined data frame. I used the paste function with the space separator to produce the titles of the graphs. I am including two different sample outputs below.
city_hist <- function (city_name, year) {
  # Convert city_name argument to string if passed as a symbol
  city_name <- as.character(toupper((substitute(city_name))))
  
  #Make a version for the ggplot
  city_name_formatted <- tools::toTitleCase(tolower(city_name))
  
  # Check if the combination of city and year exists in the data
  if (!(city_name %in% unique(joined_data$city_name) && year %in% unique(joined_data$year))) {
    stop("This combination of city and year does not exist in the dataset.")
  }

  
  joined_data %>%
    filter(city_name == !!city_name, year == !!year) %>%
    ggplot(aes(log(rainfall))) +
    geom_histogram(fill = "blue", color = "black") +
    labs(title = paste("Rainfall Histogram for", city_name_formatted, "in", year),
         x = "Log of Rainfall in mm",
         y = "Frequency") 
}

## Part 4: Apply functions and plot ### Part 4A: Tasks

  1. First, I filtered for years from 2014 onward.
  2. Then, I grouped the data by city and by year, and used summarize, applying the sample_mean() and sample_sd() functions to the grouped data on rainfall.
  3. I struggled with how to use the confidence interval output, ultimately producing it as a list and then turning it into two new columns subsequently using sapply and mutate.
  4. I named the summarized dataset rain_df.
rain_df <- joined_data %>% 
  filter(year >= 2014) %>%
  group_by(city_name, year) %>%
  summarise(mean_rainfall = sample_mean(rainfall), sd = sample_sd(rainfall), 
            CI = list(calculate_CI(rainfall))) %>%
  mutate(
    CI_LB = sapply(CI, function(x) x[["lower_bound"]]),  # Extract lower bounds
    CI_UB = sapply(CI, function(x) x[["upper_bound"]])   # Extract upper bounds
  ) %>%
  select(-CI)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'city_name'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
